When a melaleuca tree began flowering outside his house on a busy main road in Brisbane, a thought struck James Dorey:Would any native bees be attracted to this unlikely spot? Several times a day he'd go out with his insect net and swish it through the tree, jumping up to get at the high branches. "I got a few funny looks from the neighbours," he says drily. After three days he had 36 species and a fascinating insight into the secret lives of these insects, going about their business otherwise unnoticed in the heart of a capital city. Dorey painstakingly compiled this photo of his specimens - and then discovered, too late, that there's an interloper: one's a wasp, not a bee. Can you pick it? http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/heart-of-the-nation-the-secret-life-of-bee/news-story/697874330b7f10989293f8035b38ddd2
